[src:angleball/1881-penn-state-football-team] The **1881 Penn State football team** was an American football team that represented Pennsylvania State College—now known as Pennsylvania State University–during the 1881 college football season.
[src:angleball/1881-penn-state-football-team] It was the first football team fielded by the school.
[src:angleball/1881-penn-state-football-team] Penn State played only one game in 1881, beating Lewisburg by a score of 9–0.
[src:angleball/1881-penn-state-football-team] Although this game was reported in the two State College newspapers and *The Mirror*, the University at Lewisburg campus newspaper, Bucknell denies that this game ever happened.
[src:angleball/1881-penn-state-football-team] Penn State did not field teams from 1882 through 1886.
[src:angleball/1887-penn-state-football-team] The **1887 Penn State football team** was an American football team that represented Pennsylvania State College—now known as Pennsylvania State University–as an independent during the 1887 college football season.
[src:angleball/1887-penn-state-football-team] The team went 2–0 and are the school's only unscored-upon team.
[src:angleball/1887-penn-state-football-team] The captain and quarterback of the team was George H.
[src:angleball/1887-penn-state-football-team] He later changed his last name from Linsz to Lins, probably during World War I.
[src:angleball/1887-penn-state-football-team] In 1887, Penn State's school colors were dark pink and black.
[src:angleball/1888-penn-state-football-team] The **1888 Penn State football team** was an American football team that represented Pennsylvania State College—now known as Pennsylvania State University–as an independent during the 1888 college football season.
[src:angleball/1888-penn-state-football-team] The team played its home games on the Old Main lawn in University Park, Pennsylvania.
[src:angleball/1888-penn-state-football-team] The 1888 team is the only winless team in Penn State history.
[src:angleball/1888-penn-state-football-team] Harry Leyden played quarterback in 1888.
[src:angleball/1889-penn-state-football-team] The **1889 Penn State football team** was an American football team that represented Pennsylvania State College—now known as Pennsylvania State University–as an independent during the 1889 college football season.
[src:angleball/1890-penn-state-football-team] The **1890 Penn State football team** was an American football team that represented Pennsylvania State College—now known as Pennsylvania State University–as an independent during the 1890 college football season.
[src:angleball/1891-penn-state-football-team] The **1891 Penn State football team** was an American football team that represented Pennsylvania State College—now known as Pennsylvania State University–as a member of the Pennsylvania Intercollegiate Football Association (PIFA) during the 1891 college football season.
[src:angleball/1892-penn-state-football-team] The **1892 Penn State football team** was an American football team that represented Pennsylvania State College—now known as Pennsylvania State University–as an independent during the 1892 college football season.
[src:angleball/1892-penn-state-football-team] Hoskins and played its home games on the Old Main lawn in University Park, Pennsylvania.
[src:angleball/angleball] Two large target-balls are placed on standards at opposite sides of a field, however half-field can also be played The Angleball can be run or passed.
[src:angleball/angleball] Angleball can be played with varying levels of contact: non-contact, touch-contact, and full-contact; this is similar to flag, touch and tackle football.
[src:angleball/angleball] It is also often played that a pass cannot touch the ground, and that a circle key surrounds each standard that the offense cannot step inside; club variations are welcome within the Angleball community.
[src:angleball/angleball] Complete competition rules can be found on the Angleball company website .
[src:angleball/angleball] Angleball can be played with as few as 1 v 1 with a single standard placed against a rebound wall, all the way up to 100 v 100 with a standard at both ends of a park or camp.
[src:angleball/angleball] The Angleball Championship has been held annually since 2014.
[src:angleball/angleball] The first high school game played was in the late 1960s at Pioneer Ranch in Tidioute, Pennsylvania, when the Corry High School Beavers football team hosted the Titusville Rockets team.
[src:angleball/angleball] Corry's athletic director and head football coach, Lou Hanna, and Titusville's athletic director, Roy Van Horn, had been teammates on the 1939 Slippery Rock State Teachers College undefeated championship football team.
[src:angleball/angleball] Van Horn was the owner of Pioneer Ranch, a boys camp on the Allegheny River near Tidioute, Pennsylvania.
[src:angleball/angleball] With Hanna, he founded the Northwestern Pennsylvania Football Camp at Pioneer Ranch in 1961, the nation's first summertime football camp for high school gridders, and hired Penn State's coaches to staff it.
[src:angleball/angleball] It was here a relationship with Rip Engle was formed, and they were first introduced to anejodi.
[src:angleball/angleball] In the mid-1990s the game was also introduced to students at Taylor University in Upland, Indiana by Philosophy Professor, Dr.
[src:angleball/angleball] Spiegel had first learned of the sport from Dr.
[src:angleball/angleball] Wynn Kenyon at Belhaven College in the 1980s.
[src:angleball/angleball] On October 4, 2009 Angleball was introduced to a group of about 20 people in Tucson, Arizona.
[src:angleball/angleball] Angleball sets are manufactured by the American association and are being used in the NFL and by Colleges, camps, schools, and all age groups throughout the United States and Canada.
[src:angleball/angleball] In 2011 at the 100th year celebration of the Dept. of Kinesiology at Penn State, an Angleball association set was featured in "The Ball Games of the World Exhibit" presented by Dr.
[src:angleball/angleball] Ken Swalgin, Associate Professor of Kinesiology.
[src:angleball/angleball] The exhibit includes over 80 balls, equipment, and posters depicting ball sports from around the world.
[src:angleball/angleball] Ball sports are categorized as follows: handball games, bowls and bowling, ball and bat games, racket and paddle games, football games, ball and raised goal games, invasion goal games, and other ball games.(Swalgin, K.L.
[src:angleball/angleball] In 2012, an Angleball set was adopted by the NFL's Philadelphia Eagles for preseason conditioning.
[src:angleball/angleball] In September 2013, American Angleball sponsored the first angleball match in Africa (Masaka, Uganda) with the help of Sporting Is The Answer.
